<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-gradient-descent">
  <title>Gradient descent</title>

  <objectives>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Describe gradient descent as an iterative method based on moving in the direction of <m>-\Grad f</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Extend gradient descent to constrained problems using the Lagrangian <m>\cl{L}=f+\lambda(c-g)</m> and a descent-ascent update rule.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Interpret the multiplier <m>\lambda</m> as measuring how the optimal value responds to changes in the constraint.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </objectives>
  
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Introduction will go here.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <ul>

    <li>
      <p>
        If <m>f(x,y)</m> is a differentiable function, the direction of steepest decrease at a point is <m>-\,\Grad f</m>.
        This suggests the iterative scheme
        <me>
          \bv{x}_{k+1} = \bv{x}_k - \alpha \Grad f(\bv{x}_k),
        </me>
        where <m>\alpha &gt; 0</m> is a step size.
      </p>
      <p>
        For suitable choices of <m>\alpha</m>, this process moves downhill and can converge to a local minimum.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Now suppose we want to optimize <m>f(x,y)</m> subject to the constraint <m>g(x,y)=c</m>.
        Previously, we saw that a constrained extremum satisfies
        <me>
          \Grad f = \lambda \Grad g.
        </me>
        Rather than solving this system algebraically, we introduce the Lagrangian:
        <me>
          \cl{L}(x,y,\lambda)=f(x,y)+\lambda(c-g(x,y)).
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        The stationary conditions <m>\Grad_{x,y,\lambda}\cl{L}=0</m> reproduce the Lagrange multiplier equations:
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\pdv{f}{x} - \lambda\pdv{g}{x} \amp = 0</mrow>
        <mrow>\pdv{f}{y} - \lambda\pdv{g}{y} \amp = 0</mrow>
        <mrow>c - g(x,y) \amp = 0</mrow>
      </md>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        However, instead of minimizing <m>\cl{L}</m> in all variables (which would fail, since the critical point is always a saddle point), 
        we use a combined descent-ascent strategy:
      </p>
      <me>
        \bv{x}_{k+1} = \bv{x}_k - \alpha \Grad_{x,y}\cl{L},
      </me>
      <me>
        \lambda_{k+1} = \lambda_k + \beta \pdv{\cl{L}}{\lambda}.
      </me>
      <p>
        The variables <m>(x,y)</m> move in the direction that decreases <m>f</m>, while <m>\lambda</m> adjusts to enforce the constraint.
        When this system settles, we recover the constrained optimum.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        What does <m>\lambda</m> represent?
        Since
        <me>
          \pdv{\cl{L}}{c} = \lambda,
        </me>
        the multiplier measures how the Lagrangian changes when the constraint level <m>c</m> changes.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Let <m>(x^{*}(c),y^{*}(c))</m> denote the constrained optimizer and consider the optimal value
        <me>
          f(x^{*}(c),y^{*}(c)).
        </me>
        Differentiating with respect to <m>c</m> and using the chain rule together with 
        <me>
          \Grad f = \lambda \Grad g,
        </me>
        one finds
        <me>
          \dv{f}{c} = \lambda.
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>
        Thus the Lagrange multiplier measures the sensitivity of the optimal value to changes in the constraint.
      </p>
    </li>

  </ul>
</section>